at training schedules need to meet numerous demands, and that AEMMA trainers also need to fit sessions within their own schedules.\r\n4. What do you/did you think of the instructors? Offer a brief explanation.  Answered in part above.  In addition, I found the instructors to be helpful and supportive with all students.  They understood the subject matter well, and were frequently able to provide advice and suggestions that benefitted my training.  I was also impressed with the number of trainers that were typically at hand.  I felt this allowed all of the students to benefit from more individual attention.  The trainers were all very approachable, open to questions, and willing to provide explanations and advice as needed.\r\n5. Did you feel that the monthly training fees mapped well with the services offered?  How do the fees compare to other martial arts schools you know of?  I havent attended other martial arts schools, but I felt the training fees were appropriate.\r\n6. How long did you train at AEMMA before leaving the Academy?  I trained at AEMMA (not including at the ROM) for nearly two years.  However, my training was intermittent with several breaks over that time.\r\n7. What caused your long-term absence (no details, just high level description)?  With a young family at home, it became increasingly difficult to train regularly and manage my commitments to my family.  This is not a reflection on AEMMA, but a necessary short-term adjustment for myself.\r\n8. What changes or enhancements to AEMMA would be enough for you to consider returning to practices?  As mentioned above, the reasons for my absence are not related to anything specific to AEMMA.  I am hoping to return to regular training at some point in the next year as my own schedule permits.  It was with considerable regret that I stopped training, but a necessity at the time.\r\n9. Would you have any general comments or opinions about AEMMA?\r\n--------------------------------\r\nStephen was a ROM 6-