.jpg','web systems architect','M',0,0,NULL,'1965-10-13',0,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'B.CS.',NULL,0,0,NULL,1,'2005-06-30',0,'web - visit request','2006-08-15',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2005-06-30',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'AEMMA: long absence survey - Apr 4, 2008\r\nHello David,\r\n1. I visited AEMMA because I was looking for a place that addresses the historical and technical aspects of martial arts in medieval Europe and doesn\\\'t fall prey to the temptation to dress up and perform silly reenactments.\r\n2. For the most part I found the training at AEMMA engaging and insightful, however the recruit training appeared to be somewhat unstructured in the long run. As far as expectations are concerned, they were in my case fully met.\r\n3. Training: see 8). Facilities: better flooring. People: awesome people, no changes needed.\r\n4. I found the instructors, Brian, Frank, Kel and the occasional other Schollers, very effective. They all had their individual style but captured the essence of the material equally well. They were well prepared for each session and consistently addressed key points from the curriculum.\r\n5. The fees are a little above (20% in my experience) what other martial arts schools would charge, but then again AEMMA training requires significantly more space per student. One should also consider that many martial arts schools have a much larger student base to help finance operations.\r\n6. Roughly 18 months.\r\n7. Long commute coupled with scheduling conflicts with family and work. To a minor degree a diminshed motivation due to the unstructured nature of the recruit training in the later stages.\r\n8. Unrealistic enhancement: open local chapter in my area (Oakville/Burlington). Realistic enhancement: offer more structured recruit training with an emphasis on progression towards Scholler challenge. Have AEMMA instructors issue Scholler challenge instead of the student. Assist in the procurement of necessary equipm