NULL,NULL),(351,3,2,3,'AEMMA','Mark',NULL,'Childerson','Mr.','Mr. M. Childerson','495 Euclid Ave.',NULL,NULL,'Toronto','ON','M6G 2T1','Canada','416 923 2547','416 963 8793',NULL,'416 821 0104','mark@childersoft.com',NULL,NULL,'http://www.aemma.org/images/bio_photos/bio_mchilderson.jpg','http://www.aemma.org/arms/a/aemma_80.jpg','software architect','M',0,0,NULL,'1966-08-06',0,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'B.Sc.','UofT',0,0,NULL,0,'2006-11-22',0,'ROM grad Apr 16-May28 2005','2007-04-15','2006-11-22',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'AEMMA long-term absence survey - Apr 4, 2008\r\nHi David,\r\nThanks for sending this email (even if it was automatic). I started at AEMMA because I enjoyed the course at the ROM, and because my wife Orla offered to come for a year as a birthday present for me. As you can imagine, with three kids (ages 3, 7, and 10), we are pretty busy, and finding time for fitness, recreation, and, importantly, time for Orla and me to spend together as a couple, is extremely difficult. I think that we weren\\\'t quite ready for the time commitment that the art of arms requires. However, as the kids get older, the sheer logistical effort of life tends to diminish, and a return to training, either for both of us or for me in my own, is very likely to happen at some point in the (hopefully not too distant) future.\r\nI enjoyed the training greatly, and felt that it met my expectations. My recommendations (more to suit me than because I want to defend these as general policy) are:\r\n1. Air condition the salle - we stopped going in May 2007, by which time things were getting pretty hot. Orla, being Irish, was not able to cope with the idea of training at 30 degree temperatures. I realize that this could be expensive, but I would certainly be willing to pay an extra $10-$15 per month for an A/C system. I don\\\'t know if that would be popular with other members, though.\r\n2. Ridiculous as it may seem, a 7PM class would help a lot. It is difficult for me to get home from work and see the kids in time to be at class by 6 PM, and 10PM is pretty late to wrap up when getting the kids to school requires a 6:30 AM rising time in the morning. 7PM would allow for a quick hello to the kids before class, with a short dinner/unwinding to follow after class, with the kids having been put to bed by the babysitter.\r\nI was pleased with the instructors. Ross, Aldo, and Brian in particular were very helpful and capable.\r\nFees were fine - quite reasonable.\r\nI was at the academy from about Nov 2006 to May 2007.\r\nI can\\\'t quite remember why we stopped going - a few illnesses with the kids, the increasing heat, and preparation for our trip out West in the summer, caused our activity level to grow too high for getting to the school. Then we were away for a couple of months, and Orla was sick last fall - just a bunch of relatively small things, really.\r\nI think a return to training is mostly up to me, although the changes I mentioned would definitely help.\r\nI just want to say thank you, David, for your dedication and commitment to the art. I think that the school is a terrific thing to have in our city, even if I am (temporarily) unable to attend.\r\nThanks,\r\nMark\r\n***********************************'),(353,2,1,1,'AEMMA','Bill',NULL,'Brickman','Mr.','Mr. B. Brickman','52 Argyle St.',NULL,NULL,'Stratford','ON','N5A 2H5','Canada','(519) 272-2359',NULL,NULL,NULL,'wbrickman@sympatico.ca','Andria Brickman','(519) 272-2359','http://www.aemma.org/images/bio_photos/bio_bbrickman.jpg','http://www.aemma.org/arms/a/aemma_80.jpg','Data Specialist with Schaeffler','M',2,1,'Andria','1976-06-03',0,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,0,NULL,1,'2005-09-15',0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'No prescription medication, no allergies, no long term injuries\r\n\r\n',0,NULL,NULL,'Bill is the 5th Scholar from Guelph. During his scholler test, he was suffering from a cold, however, upon further diagnostics at 